docs.abstract: A New York Times/Siena College poll found Democrats faring far worse than they have in the past with Hispanic voters. But overall, the party has maintained a hold on the Latino electorate.
docs.snippet: A New York Times/Siena College poll found Democrats faring far worse than they have in the past with Hispanic voters. But overall, the party has maintained a hold on the Latino electorate.
docs.lead_paragraph: It has been nearly two years since Donald Trump made surprising gains with Hispanic voters. But Republican dreams of a major realignment of Latino voters drawn to G.O.P. stances on crime and social issues have failed to materialize, according to a new poll by The New York Times and Siena College.

headline.main: Majority of Latino Voters Out of G.O.P.’s Reach, New Poll Shows
headline.print_headline: Hispanic Voters  Still Lean Blue,  Poll Concludes

docs.abstract: While compellingly readable, Peniel E. Joseph’s “The Third Reconstruction” overstates the impact of the recent reckoning over racial justice.
docs.snippet: While compellingly readable, Peniel E. Joseph’s “The Third Reconstruction” overstates the impact of the recent reckoning over racial justice.
docs.lead_paragraph: If racial progress in America tends to arrive in waves, much of it has come in the form of two crashing breakers: the First Reconstruction, which ended slavery after the Civil War, and the Second, which ended Jim Crow segregation a century later. The historian Peniel E. Joseph believes we have just witnessed a third such moment, bracketed by Barack Obama’s election in 2008 and the wake of George Floyd’s murder in 2020.

headline.main: A Premature Victory Lap for Black Lives Matter

docs.abstract: At a time of social turmoil, Luke Mogelson’s “The Storm Is Here” explores how we got to this point.
docs.snippet: At a time of social turmoil, Luke Mogelson’s “The Storm Is Here” explores how we got to this point.
docs.lead_paragraph: To get a feel for Luke Mogelson’s new book, you might watch a bit of the footage he captured during the Jan. 6 Capitol siege. You’ll hear “traitors to the guillotine” and “kill Mike Pence” bizarrely juxtaposed with “protect the Constitution” and “Christ is king.” At one point, protesters smash video equipment taken from news crews, pile it up and set it on fire. “There you go,” someone shouts, addressing journalists trying to report the event. “Now you can’t!”

headline.main: A New Book Tracks the Rise of Right-Wing Extremism in the U.S.

docs.abstract: An argument at Arizona State’s multicultural center spiraled into a disaster for everyone involved. Who was to blame?
docs.snippet: An argument at Arizona State’s multicultural center spiraled into a disaster for everyone involved. Who was to blame?
docs.lead_paragraph: I first heard about the video from a colleague and friend at my university as we waited in line to pick up our kids after school in late September 2021. One of her students was in the video, and it had gone viral, she said. She’d posted something in support of that student, but then she also started getting attacked. Another professor at our university, Arizona State, would later call the attackers “vultures,” the kind of people who feed off moments of everyday life that morph into spectacle after an article or tweet or video goes viral. But at the time, I didn’t have that analogy. My friend told me she was scared, and I said I was sorry. By that point, she had already taken down her post.

headline.main: The Safe Space That Became a Viral Nightmare
headline.print_headline: When a Campus Clash is Caught on Video

docs.lead_paragraph: Since “Queen Sugar” debuted on the Oprah Winfrey Network in September 2016, it has been lauded for its intricate, intimate portrayal of Black Southern life, told through the prism of one family — the Bordelons — and their struggle to preserve their land and legacy in the fictional St. Josephine Parish in Louisiana.
